                          	 <td valign="top">
                         		<div align="justify">
                          		<p>
									<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#333333" style="font-size:12px;">When it comes to making investments people are often confused whether to opt for a ULIP (Unit Linked Insurance Plan) or a mutual fund. Adding to the confusion is that assumption that investment in a ULIP plan and in a mutual fund gives similar return(say 10%) and that after a period of 10 years or so ULIP plans beat mutual fund in terms of returns generated.<br /><br />
											<strong>The basis for assumptions</strong><br />
											This is due to the fact that in the initial years in a ULIP plan the extra charges (Premium allocation charges, commissions etc.)are present which are not charged later. Hence, from the 4th or 5th year onwards, after deducting the mortality charges and policy admin charges, the entire premium in a ULIP is allocated for investment.<br/><br/>
											Till the 8th or 10thyear the returns on a mutual fund will be more than a ULIP plan because of the initial charges. However, as the tenure increases, the ULIP plans race ahead of the mutual fund because of the difference in Fund Management Charges (FMC).The FMC  in ULIPsare generally in the range of 0.75% to 1.30% and the FMC in equity mutual funds would generally be in the range of 1.75% to 2.25%. Moreover,since the Regulator has put restrictions like keeping the agents commission to maximum 8% in the first year and also capping all the costs to 2.25% of the premiums paid for a policy of tenure above 10 years, ULIPs have become more attractive.<br/><br/>
											<strong>The facts about ULIPs and mutual funds</strong><br />
											Firstly the basic assumption that mutual funds and ULIP plans give identical returns is flawed. There are many equity oriented funds in the market whichhave consistently given a return of more than 22% per but same thing cannot be said about the ULIP plans.<br /><br />
											Secondly, the structure of ULIPs (as explained earlier) calls for people to be stayed invested ina ULIP plan for a long time. Hence,if you have an emergency and if you then need funds, liquidating a ULIP plan would not be a good idea. However, if you need to redeem the units invested in mutual funds you can still benefit from better returns sincein the initial years a mutual fund performs better than ULIP plan. <br /><br />
											Thirdly, another drawback is that fact that one is deprived of choices when it comes to a ULIP plan as you can only change the component of your investment in equity and debt. In a scenario where you wish to stay invested in equity only, you cannot change your investment from a non performing equity fund to another in case of a ULIP plan. <br /><br />
											Fourthly, the insurance component (for which mortality charges are charged by the company) of an ULIP plan is an area of concern for two reasons – 
									</font>
								</p>
	                            <ol>
	                            	<li><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#333333"  style="font-size:12px;">You don’t get sufficient cover for the premiumyou have paid. <br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;</font></li>
									<li><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#333333" style="font-size:12px;">You would not know the actual amount of insurance cover you need.</font><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
								</ol>
								<p>
									<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#333333" style="font-size:12px;"> There is a science attached to finding your insurance cover required by a person which is referred as HUMAN LIFE VALUE. <br /><br />
									Therefore,oneshould never mix insurance with investments. Insurance is meant to cover risk in/ofyour life and not be used as investment tool.By combining term insurance with investments in Mutual Funds (either as alump suminvestmentor as a monthly SIP) will ultimately fetch you better returns rather than going for any traditional insurance policies or ULIP plans.
									</font>
